The Model-View-Controller (MVC) pattern is a widely used architectural pattern in software development that separates an application into three interconnected components.

**Model**

The Model represents the data and business logic of the application. It is responsible for managing the data and performing any necessary calculations or operations on it.

**View**

The View is responsible for rendering the user interface (UI) of the application. It displays the data provided by the Model to the user.

**Controller**

The Controller acts as an intermediary between the Model and the View. It receives input from the user, interacts with the Model to retrieve or update data, and then updates the View with the new data.

